Inside `getScopes`, you are filling `tempScopes` in a `then` of a Promise, which is run *asynchronously*.
But below it you are also calling `setState` immediately, which means at the time you call `setState`, `tempScopes` array is still empty. 
You should move call to `setState` also inside `then`. Something like this:

      

           .then((querySnapshot) =&gt; {
                querySnapshot.forEach(function(doc) {
                    tempScopes.push(doc.data().address);
                })
                this.setState({scopes:tempScopes});
            })

As in usual fashion, the answer came to me moments after posting. I think the issues stemmed from the binding of this within the getScopes function. This code fixed the issue.

    getScopes() {
  		let tempScopes = [];
  		this.props.firebase.db.collection(&quot;scopes&quot;).where(&quot;status&quot;, &quot;==&quot;, 1).get()
  			.then( (querySnapshot) =&gt; (
        		querySnapshot.forEach( (doc) =&gt; (
        			this.setState((prevState) =&gt; ({
        				scopes: [ ...this.state.scopes, doc.data().address ]
        			}))
            	))
        	))
    		.catch(function(error) {
        		console.log(&quot;Error getting documents: &quot;, error);
    		});
  	}

