just try 
```css
.logo-container {
  background:red;
  display:flex;
  justify-content:center;
  width:100%;
}
```
flexbox are a pretty good thing to center element

Here is the code that will center your image.
```

.logo-container {
  /* text-align: center; */
  width: 100%; // added this
  display: grid; // added this
}

.logo {
  display: block;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding-top: 150px;
  justify-self: center; // added this
  /* text-align: center; */
  /* float: left; */

}
```

-The *width: 100%* stretches the div&#39;s width to be equal to the parent container. Without this, the div&#39;s width would be the image&#39;s width == No centering.

-The *display: grid* declares the div to be a grid item. It makes the div function kinda like a table with rows and columns. However, the coolest thing about grid is it can center its child elements for you through the *justify-contents* or the *justify-self* attribute.

-The *justify-self: center* make the element centered within its parent element. This is only possible if the parent is a grid (above) or a flexbox which is another wonderful choice. In face, you can replace *display: grid* with *display: flex* and you&#39;d get the same result.



**Extra advice:** 

-It&#39;s really cool that you are exploring css. I definitely recommend looking up css flexbox and grid. These two displays helped me immensely when I started using css more seriously.  



**Links:**

-Grid (Basic): https://www.w3schools.com/css/css_grid.asp

-Grid (More Advance): https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/complete-guide-grid/

-Flexbox (Basic): https://www.w3schools.com/csS/css3_flexbox.asp

-Flexbox (More Advance): https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/

The two above answers are great solutions. Another solution I found (without using grid or flexbox) is to use the `clear:both` property. The image is attempting to `float: left` by default for some reason.

Also, when using `margin: 0 auto;` be sure to explicitly set `position: relative;` otherwise it will not work.

Here are all my changes to your css:

    .logo-container {
      position: relative;
      width: 100%;
    }
    
    .logo {
      position: relative;
      display: block;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding-top: 150px;
      clear: both;
    }

